{"questionId":"9076751","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Rhodium-106 (<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"_{\\,\\,\\,45}^{106}{\\text{Rh}}\">\n  <msubsup>\n    <mi></mi>\n    <mrow>\n      <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      <mn>45</mn>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>106</mn>\n    </mrow>\n  </msubsup>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>Rh</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>)&nbsp;decays into palladium-106 (<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"_{\\,\\,\\,46}^{106}{\\text{Pd}}\">\n  <msubsup>\n    <mi></mi>\n    <mrow>\n      <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      <mn>46</mn>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>106</mn>\n    </mrow>\n  </msubsup>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>Pd</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>)&nbsp;by beta minus (<em>β</em><sup>–</sup>) decay.&nbsp;The diagram shows some of the nuclear energy levels of rhodium-106 and palladium-106.&nbsp;The arrow represents the <em>β</em><sup>–</sup> decay.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"https://ib-questionbank-attachments.s3.amazonaws.com/uploads/tinymce_asset/asset/4850/Schermafbeelding_2018-08-14_om_06.42.36.png\" alt=\"M18/4/PHYSI/HP2/ENG/TZ2/09.d\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Suggest why the <em>β</em><sup>–</sup> decay is followed by the emission of a gamma ray photon.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>the palladium nucleus emits the photon when it decays into the ground state <strong>«</strong>from the excited state<strong>»</strong></p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9076751","referenceCode":"18M.2.HL.TZ2.9d.ii","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"Suggest why the β– decay is followed by the emission of a gamma